The mandate to allow amendments necessary for the purpose of avoiding a multiplicity of proceedings may be most readily explicable against the background of the historical differences between common law and equity courts: see Aon Risk Services Australia Ltd v Australian National University (2009) 258 ALR 14; 83 ALJR 951; [2009] HCA 27;  BC200906905 at [11] , [17]. Because of the statutory mandates to determine the “real issues” (see CPA 
s 56(1)
) and give such judgment “as the nature of the case requires” (see CPA 
s 90
) the capacity for multiple proceedings in relation to “real issues” is somewhat limited perhaps especially in the Supreme Court given the additional obligations of finality imposed by SCA ss 62, 63. This view, perhaps not immediately apparent from the terms of the section itself, is further encouraged by the extent to which principles of issue estoppel, the kind of estoppel discussed in Port of Melbourne Authority v Anshun Pty Ltd (1981) 147 CLR 589; 36 ALR 3;  BC8100097  (see 
[14.28.20]
), and abuse of process (see 
[14.28.5]
) could operate to preclude the subsequent litigation of similar and related issues: Aon Risk Services Australia Ltd v Australian National University (2009) 258 ALR 14; 83 ALJR 951; [2009] HCA 27;  BC200906905 at [32]–[34] , [86], [87].

Relevant “prejudice” in this context is not directly concerned with the merits of the matter sought to be raised. It is only concerned with the consequences of the time and manner of the amendment. Accordingly the stage of the proceedings when the amendment is sought will often be significant and may be determinative — depending upon the nature of the amendment. See further [
s 64.30
].

Between these extremes the precise characterisation of the nature of the amendment, whether or not the relevant limitation period has expired, and whether or not there is an available power to amend, may be both difficult, and undesirable, to determine at an interlocutory hearing: Wardley Australia Ltd v Western Australia (1992) 175 CLR 514 at 533; 109 ALR 247;  BC9202700 . In such instances it may be appropriate to allow the amendment on terms that defers final determination of the date the amendment takes effect: Integral Energy v EDS (Aust) Ltd [2006] NSWSC 600;  BC200604564 . Apart from instances of that kind, the power to “otherwise order” under this rule has been used to enable a plaintiff to amend to rely upon the Trade Practices Act 1974 (Cth) (now the 
Competition and Consumer Act 2010
) even though the statement of claim was first filed before the court had jurisdiction under that legislation: Australia & New Zealand Banking Group Ltd v Larcos (1987) 13 NSWLR 286 ; Barina Properties Pty Ltd v Waring  (SC(NSW), Greenwood M, No 19018/86, 13 May 1991, unreported, BC9102003).

